@node not25 "ACTIVE TECHNOLOGIES ANNOUNCE GENESIS, A NEW TCP/IP STACK FOR THE AMIGA"

@{B}ACTIVE TECHNOLOGIES@{UB} ANNOUNCE @{B}GENESIS@{UB}, A NEW TCP/IP STACK FOR THE @{B}AMIGA@{UB}
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@{B}Genesis@{UB}  is  a  state-of-the-art  TCP/IP stack for the @{B}Amiga@{UB} computer. Combining
ease  of  use  with  advanced  features, @{B}Genesis@{UB} offers built in dialup Internet
connectivity and/or local area networking.

@{B}Genesis@{UB} requires @{B}Magic User Interface@{UB} (@{B}v3.8+@{UB}) in order to operate.

Further  information can be obtained from @{B}www.vapor.com@{UB} or @{B}www.active-net.co.uk@{UB}.
A  demo  is  also  available and you can register online via the @{B}Vapor@{UB} automatic
registration form.

Feature list includes:
  * Easy to setup. The software is fully configurable via a custom interface, no
    need  to  edit text files. Offers simplicity, enabling a beginner to be able
    to  setup  their  stack  within  minutes,  yet keeping the advanced features
    needed for the professional user.
  * Compatibility.  @{B}Genesis@{UB}  is  fully  compatible  with existing @{B}Amiga@{UB} Internet
    software. Based on the recognised and established @{B}AmiTCP Professional@{UB} kernel
    (@{B}v4.6@{UB}),  @{B}Genesis@{UB}  offers  the  highest possible compatibility with other net
    products, no need for @{B}AmiTCP@{UB} emulation.
  * Built-in  support.  @{B}Genesis@{UB}  ships with modules for @{B}PPP@{UB}, @{B}(C)SLIP@{UB} and support
    for other variations such as @{B}SANA-II@{UB} etc. Supports Internet access by modem,
    external @{B}ISDN TA@{UB}, internal @{B}ISDN@{UB} boards, ethernet (such as @{B}Ariadne@{UB} or @{B}Hydra@{UB}),
    serial  cards  (@{B}Hypercom@{UB},  @{B}IOBlix@{UB},  @{B}GVP-IO@{UB}  etc)  and  other  local networks
    (parnet, null modem etc).
  * Advanced  @{B}PPP@{UB} implementation: @{B}(MS)CHAP@{UB}, @{B}PAP@{UB}, @{B}Callback@{UB} (@{B}WinNT@{UB} compatible), @{B}VJ@{UB}
    compression,  protocol  field  compression,  @{B}MTU@{UB}  negotiation,  magic number
    negotiation, async map negotiation, @{B}MSDNS1/2@{UB} IP address negotiation, @{B}WINS1/2@{UB}
    IP  address negotiation, Compression Control Protocol (modules include - @{B}BSD@{UB}
    compress,  deflate  and @{B}MPPC@{UB}). Also, @{B}PPP@{UB} events control allows you to create
    scripts to perform actions when @{B}PPP@{UB} has been put on or offline.
  * Dial  control.  Teach-me  dialer,  multiple phone numbers, configurable dial
    script.
  * Comprehensive  security.  Secure  kernel to prevent illegal attacks over the
    Internet:  @{B}SYN@{UB}  flooding, IP fragment attacks, IP address spoofing, land and
    fist attacks.
  * Enhanced  @{B}SANA-II@{UB}.  Powerful and improved @{B}SANA-II@{UB} support allows the fastest
    transfer rates across an ethernet network.
  * Connection  Wizard.  Step  by step Wizard interface to connect a user to the
    Internet. Enter basic information, Wizard obtains the IP and DNS information
    automatically and records your loginscript.
  * Arexx  interface and improved API - allows external software to check status
    of interfaces, logged in user, active user and much more.
  * @{B}Socks@{UB}.  @{B}Socks v4@{UB}/@{B}5@{UB} client supplied as standard. @{B}Socks@{UB} server avaialble, free
    of charge, as a downloadable option.
  * Multiple  interface  support. This allows you to connect and disconnect more
    than  one  interface  at  one  time. For instance, create two ethernet links
    between an @{B}Amiga@{UB} and @{B}Linux@{UB} machine and another between your @{B}Amiga@{UB} and @{B}PC@{UB} and
    then  still  connect  and disconnect from your Internet (dialup) connection,
    without  the other interfaces being affected. You can even launch @{B}Genesis@{UB} on
    bootup  so  that  a  local area network is put online automatically when you
    start  your  @{B}Amiga@{UB}. This is essential for a @{B}Siamese@{UB} system, for example. You
    can  then  use  @{B}Genesis@{UB} for modem dialup or route your dialup connection via
    the  remote  computer.  Multiple  interface support is easy to setup and the
    interfaces  are  listed  within  the main status window (shown here). Allows
    routing between interfaces.
  * Multiple-user  support. Full support and API for multiple-users. Create more
    than  one  user  and  then  log-on  via the main status window (users can be
    password  protected  to  prevent unauthorised access). The multi-user API is
    currently  supported  by  a  range  of  @{B}Amiga@{UB}  Internet  software  including
    @{B}Microdot-II@{UB},  @{B}Contact  Manager@{UB}  and  soon  @{B}YAM@{UB}  (from  r7), with more in the
    future.
  * Multiple  providers.  Add multiple providers or provider configurations with
    ease,  then  select these providers by point and click, from the main status
    window.  You  might be testing two providers with a 30-day trial? Setup both
    providers and flick between them.
  * Access  control.  Parents  have full time/access control over each user. The
    system  manager  can  setup  time  limitations  (for example a user could be
    prevented  from  connecting  during  the working hours 09:00-18:00). @{B}Genesis@{UB}
    will  double-check  the  current time on connection, so that the user cannot
    temporarily  alter  the  system clock to fool software into thinking it is a
    weekend, for instance.
  * Advanced  time/cost logger. Shows each user access (or overall access), time
    and  date and the cost of this access. @{B}Genesis@{UB} shows statistical information
    to help you monitor Internet costs and time usage.

